\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=2cm]

% Define styles for nodes
\tikzstyle{variable} = [circle, draw, fill=blue!30, minimum size=15pt]
\tikzstyle{factor}   = [rectangle, draw, fill=red!30, minimum width=20pt, minimum height=15pt]

% Random Variables (Circles)
\foreach \i in {1,...,5} {
    \node[variable] (V\i) at (\i*2,0) {$X_{\i}$};
}

% Factor Nodes (Squares)
\foreach \j in {1,...,3} {
    \node[factor] (F\j) at (\j*2,-2) {$\mu_{\j}$};
}

% Draw edges between variables and factors
\foreach \i in {1,...,5} {
    \foreach \j in {1,...,3} {
        \draw[-stealth] (V\i) -- (F\j);
    }
}

\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

### Explanation:
- **Nodes**: 
  - `variable`: Represents each patient. Here, we have 5 patients labeled \( X_1, X_2, X_3, X_4, X_5 \).
  - `factor`: Represents each factor node. Here, we have 3 factor nodes labeled \( \mu_1, \mu_2, \mu_3 \).

- **Edges**:
  - The `\foreach` loops ensure that each variable node is connected to each factor node, creating a complete bipartite graph \( K_{5,3} \). 

### Customization:
- You can adjust the number of patients (`N`) by changing the range in the first `\foreach` loop.
- Similarly, you can change the number of factor nodes (`K`) by adjusting the range in the second `\foreach` loop.
